{
  "id": "volatility_adaptive_breakout_strategy",
  "name": "Volatility Adaptive Breakout Strategy",
  "description": "This strategy aims to capitalize on breakout opportunities by identifying periods of price compression relative to recent volatility. By using the 14-period Average True Range (ATR) to gauge volatility and volume contraction, the strategy seeks to enter trades aligned with the short-term directional bias on a 15-minute timeframe.",
  "algorithm_type": "TechnicalPattern",
  "prompt": "I want to develop a volatility-adaptive breakout strategy trading on a 15-minute timeframe. The core idea is to identify periods of compressed price range relative to recent volatility and volume contraction, then enter breakouts aligned with short-term directional bias.\n\nEntry Conditions:\n- Calculate the 14-period Average True Range (ATR) and normalize it by dividing ATR by the 14-period simple moving average (SMA) of the closing price to get a volatility ratio.\n- Identify a \"compression phase\" when the current 15-minute bar\u2019s range (High - Low) is less than 40% of the ATR, and the 14-period volume SMA is decreasing for at least 3 consecutive periods, indicating volume contraction.\n- Use a 7-period EMA and a 21-period EMA on closing prices for trend bias: only consider long entries if EMA7 > EMA21, short entries if EMA7 < EMA21.\n- Enter long when price breaks above the highest high of the last 5 bars during compression with the bias long.\n- Enter short when price breaks below the lowest low of the last 5 bars during compression with the bias short.\n\nExit Conditions:\n- Use an adaptive trailing stop set at 1.5 times the ATR from the highest/lowest price achieved after entry.\n- Exit if the opposite breakout occurs \u2014 i.e., long exit if price breaks below the lowest low of the last 5 bars, short exit if price breaks above the highest high.\n\nThis strategy combines volatility compression with volume contraction to filter for consolidation before breakout, while integrating a dynamic trend filter and ATR-based exits to adapt to changing market conditions.",
